  <static seed="128" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/Factoring/factoring395.pg">
    <statement><p>Factor the given polynomial.</p>
<p><m>{2x^{4}+4x^{3}-16x^{2}}=</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>2x^{2}\mathopen{}\left(x-2\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+4\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>Let<rsq/>s start by noting that <m>2x^{2}</m> is a common factor to each term, so 
we may write</p>
<p><m>{2x^{4}+4x^{3}-16x^{2}}={2x^{2}\mathopen{}\left(x^{2}+2x-8\right)}</m></p>
<p>To factor this expression further we make the following observations:
<ul label="disc">
<li>
<p>the leading coefficient is 1</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>the last term is <em>negative</em> which means that the factorization will 
have the following form</p>
<p><m>(x-\phantom{3})(x+\phantom{3})</m></p>
</li>
</ul></p>
<p>We look for factors of <m>-8</m> that add to <m>2</m>; the 
factors that work are <m>-2</m> and <m>4</m> so</p>
<p><m>{2x^{4}+4x^{3}-16x^{2}}={2x^{2}\mathopen{}\left(x-2\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+4\right)}</m></p>
<p>Note that this answer can be checked by using the FOIL (<alert>F</alert>irst <alert>O</alert>utside <alert>I</alert>nside <alert>L</alert>ast) technique (exercise).</p>
</solution>
